 | main_organ = <!-- or: | publication = --> <!--Organization's principal body (assembly, committee, board, etc) or publication--> | parent_organization = [[Center for Effective Global Action]] | subsidiaries = | secessions = | affiliations = | budget = | budget_year = | staff = <!-- Numbers and/or types of staff --> | staff_year = <!-- Year to which staff numbers/data apply --> | volunteers = <!-- Numbers and/or types of volunteers --> | volunteers_year = <!-- Year to which volunteer numbers/data apply --> | website = {{url|https://www.bitss.org/}} | remarks = | formerly = <!-- Any former names by which the organization known --> | footnotes = }} The '''Berkeley Initiative for Transparency in the Social Sciences''', abbreviated '''BITSS''', is an academic initiative dedicated to advancing [[transparency]] and openness in [[social science]] research. It was established in 2012 by the [[University of California, Berkeley]]'s [[Center for Effective Global Action]]. It is led by an interdisciplinary group of academics from ten different universities.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.bitss.org/about/ |title=About |date=2015-10-08 |website=Berkeley Initiative for Transparency in the Social Sciences |language=en-US |access-date=2018-10-19}}</ref> It has worked with the [[Center for Open Science]] to define and promote a set of best practices for social scientists to maximize transparency in their research.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Miguel |first=E. |last2=Camerer |first2=C. |last3=Casey |first3=K. |last4=Cohen |first4=J. |last5=Esterling |first5=K. M. |last6=Gerber |first6=A. |last7=Glennerster |first7=R. |last8=Green |first8=D. P. |last9=Humphreys |first9=M. |date=2014-01-03 |title=Promoting Transparency in Social Science Research |url=http://science.sciencemag.org/content/343/6166/30 |journal=Science |language=en |volume=343 |issue=6166 |pages=30–31 |doi=10.1126/science.1245317 |issn=0036-8075 |pmc=4103621 |pmid=24385620}}</ref>
In 2015, the BITSS began awarding the annual Leamer-Rosenthal Prizes for Open Social Science to honor outstanding achievements in promoting transparency in social science.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/science/archive/2015/12/make-science-more-reliable-win-cash-prizes/419781/ |title=Make Science More Reliable, Win Cash Prizes |last=Yong |first=Ed |date=2015-12-10 |website=The Atlantic |language=en-US |access-date=2018-10-19}}</ref> Through its Catalyst program, the initiative also supports over 120 [[graduate student]]s who are active in advancing [[open science]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.bitss.org/catalysts/ |title=Catalysts |date=2015-12-03 |website=Berkeley Initiative for Transparency in the Social Sciences |language=en-US |access-date=2018-10-19}}</ref> ==References== {{Reflist}} ==External links== *{{Official website|https://www.bitss.org/}} {{Science-org-stub}}
