{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}} {{Infobox ethnic group |group = Indians in Luxembourg |population = 300 |popplace = [[Luxembourg (city)|Luxembourg]] |langs = [[Luxembourgish Language|Luxembourgish]]{{·}}[[German language|German]]{{·}}[[French Language|French]]{{·}}[[English language|English]]{{·}}[[Hindi]]{{·}}[[Tamil Language|Tamil]] |rels = [[Hinduism]]{{·}}[[Islam]]{{·}}[[Christianity]] |related-c = [[Non-resident Indian and person of Indian origin|People of Indian origin]] }}'''Indians in Luxembourg''' form a small minority in the country. As of 2007, there are about 30000 people of Indian origin living in [[Luxembourg]].<ref>"[http://www.dnaindia.com/world/report_indian-spirit-spices-up-luxembourg_1075694- Indian spirit spices up Luxembourg]", ''Daily News and Analysis'', 21 January 2007.</ref>
==Migration history== Since the 1980s, Indians have been coming to Luxembourg due to the growth of the IT industry in the country and the fact that the Indian company [[ArcelorMittal]] has its head office there. Today, there are about 200 Indian families living in the Grand Duchy. Most of the Indians in Luxembourg today are working in the financial sector or are into hotel management.<ref>"[http://www.wort.lu/wort/web/en/culture/articles/2011/11/167654/index.php- Indian Association of Luxembourg turns 20 - India's friendly face in Luxembourg]", ''wort.lu'', 15 November 2011.</ref><ref>"[http://www.thehindubusinessline.in/life/2007/02/02/stories/2007020200200200.htm- Indian Association of Luxembourg turns 20 - Global grand duchy]", ''The Hindu Business Line'', 2 February 2007.</ref>
==Language and religion== Indians in Luxembourg speak Indian languages such as [[Hindi]], [[Tamil Language|Tamil]] and [[Telugu Language|Telugu]] as well as local languages like [[German language|German]], [[French Language|French]] and [[Luxembourgish Language|Luxembourgish]]. [[Hinduism]], [[Islam]] and [[Christianity]] are practiced by the Indian community and festivals such as [[Diwali]], [[Eid al-Fitr|Eid]] and [[Christmas]] are celebrated.
==Organizations== The Indian Association of Luxembourg was formed in 1991 by a businessman, Ambi Venkataraman. The association was born with the help of 13 founding members and it also serves an educational role in ensuring that children with Indian heritage understand their cultural history, including the religious festivals. In November 2011, the Indian Association of Luxembourg celebrated its 20th anniversary.
