[[File:Noos Balmes 224.tiff|thumb|No. 224 Balmes Street in Barcelona, on the fourth floor of which were located Aizoon and Baf Tejeiro's social headquarters, the tax-advice office of Diego Torres' siblings-in-law]]

The '''Nóos case''', also known as the '''Babel operation''',<ref name="imputacion-palma">{{cite news|first=Andreu|last=Manresa|author2=Jesús García |title=¿Por qué la Policía llamó a la investigación sobre Urdangarín "Operación Babel"?|url=http://www.abc.es/20111229/espana/abci-operacion-babel-urdangarin-201112291829.html|accessdate=26 February 2013|date=30 December 2011|language=Spanish}}</ref> is an ongoing case of alleged [[political corruption]] in [[Spain]] which started in 2010, derived from the [[Palma Arena]] case. The leaders of the nonprofit foundation Nóos Institute, [[Iñaki Urdangarin y Liebaert|Iñaki Urdangarin]], then Duke of Palma de Mallorca, and his business partner Diego Torres have been accused of using Nóos and a corporate network of companies to [[embezzlement|embezzle]] about 6 million euros ($6.6 million) in public funds for sporting events, [[perverting the course of justice]], [[Forgery|falsification]] and [[money laundering]]. 

==The accused==
In December 2011, the judge attendant of the [[Palma Arena]] case, José Castro, charged nine individuals.<ref name="Vangimputado">{{cite news|title=Iñaki Urdangarín, imputado|url=http://www.lavanguardia.com/politica/20111229/54243737747/inaki-urdangarin-imputado.html|accessdate=24 February 2013|date=29 December 2011|publisher=La Vanguardia}}</ref> In 2013, after one of the accused, Diego Torres, had confessed, the list increased to 10.{{cn|date=September 2016}} {{as of|2016}} the list has grown to 18.<ref name="ST">{{cite news | url=http://www.startribune.com/spain-princess-husband-begins-testifying-in-fraud-case/370247371/ | title=Spain: Princess Cristina's husband testifies in fraud case | work=Star Tribune | date=26 February 2016 | agency=Associated Press | accessdate=9 September 2016 | author=ALAN CLENDENNING and CIARAN GILES}}</ref>The main defendants have been:
*[[Iñaki Urdangarin y Liebaert |Iñaki Urdangarín Liebaert]] (born on 15 January 1968), former handball player and husband of the infanta of Spain, Cristina de Borbón, daughter of King [[Juan Carlos I]]. He has been facing charges since 2012<ref name="Vangimputado"/> for using his former title of Duke of Palma to embezzle about 6 million euros ($6.6 million) in public funds for sporting events.<ref name="ST" /> On 17 February 2017, Urdangarin was given a six-year-and-three-month prison sentence for his role in the case.<ref name="BBC1">{{cite news|title=Spain's Princess Cristina cleared in tax trial|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-39005056|accessdate=17 February 2017|work=BBC News|date=17 February 2017}}</ref> In appeal the Supreme Court changed this on 12 June 2018 into a term of five years and ten months.
*Diego Torres
*[[Infanta Cristina, Duchess of Palma de Mallorca|Cristina de Borbón y Grecia, Infanta of Spain]] (born on 13 June 1965), then Duchess of Palma, daughter of King [[Juan Carlos I]] of Spain. Charged since April 2013.<ref name="Imputacion_Infanta">{{cite news|title=El juez cita como imputada a la infanta Cristina en el 'caso Urdangarín'|url=http://politica.elpais.com/politica/2013/04/03/actualidad/1364988109_049327.html |accessdate=3 April 2013|language=Spanish|publisher=El Mundo}}</ref> with two counts of tax fraud, facing a possible eight-year sentence.<ref name="ST" /> She was acquitted in February 2017 of the charges.<ref name="BBC1" />
*[[José Luis Ballester (sailor)|José Luis Ballester Tuliesa]], "Pepote" Ballester (born in 1968), former Olympic sailor, managing director of Sports of the Government of the Balearic Islands.{{cn|date=September 2016}}
*Carlos García Revenga (born in 1955), private secretary of the infantas and member of the patronate of the Queen Sofía Foundation. Licensed in Pedagogics, and Schoolteachers, former teacher of the Santa María del Camino college (Puerto del Hierro, Madrid). Charged since February 2013.<ref>{{cite news|first=Eduardo|last=Inda|title=Carlos García Revenga o la Casa Real como tarjeta de presentación|url=http://www.elmundo.es/elmundo/2013/02/22/baleares/1361561974.html|accessdate=23 February 2013|date=23 February 2013|language=Spanish|publisher=El Mundo}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Carlos García Revenga: La Sombra de Elena y Cristina|url=http://www.lavozdegalicia.es/noticia/espana/2013/01/30/carlos-garcia-revenga-sombra-elena-cristina/00031359547951493259932.htm|accessdate=25 February 2013|date=30 January 2013|language=Spanish|publisher=La Voz de Galicia}}</ref>
*[[Jaume Matas|Jaume Matas i Palou]] (Palma de Mallorca, 1956), former Balearic president, one of the first defendants. Under his term the regional executive ordered the Nóos Institute to organize two forums about tourism and sport from which Urdangarín's company supposedly pocketed €2.3 million between 2005 and 2006. {{cn|date=September 2016}}
*Miguel Zorío, owner of the company Communication Lobby and collaborator of Urdangarín and Torres as from 2004, when he managed the Valencia Summit, a sports summit that Nóos organized for the Valencian government.{{cn|date=September 2016}}

==Timeline==
In February 2006, Antoni Dieguez, a Socialist representative in the Balearic Parliament, said that the Government chaired by Jaume Matas had paid 1.2 million euros to the Nóos Institute for a 3-day forum on tourism and sport from 22 until 25 November 2005, with minimal impact.<ref name="SigloRey">{{cite news |author=V.C. |title=El Rey frena a Urdangarin |date=2 May 2006 |work=El Siglo de Europa |url=http://www.elsiglodeuropa.es/siglo/historico/2006/696/696portada.html |accessdate=18 February 2013}}</ref>

In the summer of 2007 the [[Palma Arena]] case began, when an imbalance of more than 50 million euros in the accounts of the newly opened sports center Palma Arena became public as it  had cost 110 million with a bidding price of 43 million.<ref name="elpais">{{cite news | url=http://politica.elpais.com/politica/2014/01/07/actualidad/1389109271_041224.htm | title=Del sobrecoste de un polideportivo al escándalo del ‘caso Urdangarin’ | work=El Pais | date=7 January 2014 | accessdate=9 September 2016 | author=Andreu Manresa}}</ref>

In 2010, the Nóos case was opened as derived from the [[Palma Arena]] case.<ref name = "imputation-palm">{{cite news |author = Andreu Manresa and Jesus Garcia| title = Inaki Urdangarin to be charged in the 'Palma Arena case' | url = http://politica.elpais.com/politica/2011/11/09/actualidad/1320835105_840729.html | accessdate = 20 July 2012 | date = 9 November 2011 | work = El Pais|language =Spanish}}</ref> <ref name = "log">{{cite news | author= Andreu Manresa and Jesus Garcia| title= Anticorrupción registra la fundación de Iñaki | url = http://elpais.com/diario/2011/11/08/espana/1320706816_850215.html | accessdate = 20 July 2012 | date = 8 November 2011 | publisher = El Pais|language =Spanish}}</ref> in the Palma Arena records police found two collaboration agreements between the Balearic Government and the Nóos Institute. The [[magistrate]] Jose Castro found sufficient cause to open a separate case, misappropriation of public funds, embezzlement of public funds and fraudulent administration.<ref name = "log"/>

