In South Africa, a '''tenderpreneur''' is a person in government or private sector who obtains private or government [[tendering|tender]]s and contracts to facilitate outsourced services.  The word ''tenderpreneur'' is a [[portmanteau]] of "[[tendering]]" and "[[entrepreneur]]". Some commentators believe that this practice might give rise to a [[kleptocracy]] as a deviant mutation of a democracy if left unchecked. In this regard a kleptocracy is defined at the condition arising when a political elite manipulate the three arms of government (legislature, executive and judiciary) with the intention of capturing resources that will enrich that elite,<ref>Turton, A.R [http://www.shakinghandswithbilly.comShaking Hands with Billy]{{Dead link|date=June 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=no }} Durban: Just Done Publications. 2010.</ref> a general phenomenon known as [[elite capture]]. 

''[[The Star (South Africa)|The Star]]'', a South African newspaper describes a tenderpreneur as "someone politically well-connected who has got rich through the government tendering system".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.timeslive.co.za/sundaytimes/article318330.ece|title=How Malema made his millions|publisher=''[[The Star (South Africa)|The Star]]''|date=2010-02-21}}</ref> In January 2010, [[South African Communist Party]] leader [[Blade Nzimande]] called for transparency in the awarding of tenders, saying "let's be bold, let's go and promote small entrepreneurs and defeat tenderpreneurs, those who steal."<ref>Mahlangu, Dominic. [http://www.timeslive.co.za/news/article251335.ece Blade: Make all tenders public.] ''Times LIVE.'' 6 January 2010.</ref>

